<section xml:id="sec-kernel-image-of-hom">
	<title>Kernel and image of a linear homomorphism</title>
	<introduction>We describe two important subspaces associated with a linear transformation, viz., the kernel and the image.</introduction>
	<p>
		We define the kernel of a linear transformation.
	</p>
	<definition xml:id="def-kernel">
		<statement>
			Let <m>V,W</m> be vector spaces over a field <m>F</m>, and let <m>T\colon V\to W</m> be an <m>F</m>-linear transformation. The kernel of <m>T</m> is <me>\ker(T)=\{v\in V:T(v)=0\}.</me>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<remark>
		<statement>
			Note that <m>\ker(T)=T^{-1}\{0\}.</m>
		</statement>
	</remark>
	<lemma>
	<statement>
		We keep the notations of <xref ref="def-kernel"/>. The kernel of an <m>F</m>-linear transformation is a subspace of <m>V</m>.
	</statement>
	</lemma>
	<lemma xml:id="injective-iff-kenerl-is-zero">
		<statement>
			We keep the notations of <xref ref="def-kernel"/>. The map <m>T</m> is injective if and only if <m>\ker(T)=\{0\}</m>.
		</statement>	
	</lemma>
	<proof>
		<p>
			Suppose that <m>T</m> is injective. If <m>v\in V</m> is such that <m>T(v)=0</m> then, we have <m>T(v)=T(0)=0</m> (see <xref ref="zero-maps-to-zero"/>). Injectivity of <m>T</m> implies that <m>v=0</m>.
		</p>
		<p>
			Now assume that <m>\ker(T)=0</m>. If <m>x,y\in V</m> are such that <m>T(x)=T(y)</m> then, by <m>F</m>-linearity of <m>T</m>, we have <m>T(x-y)=T(x)-T(y)=0</m>. Therefore, <m>x=y</m>.
		</p>
	</proof>

	<p>
		We now define the image of a linear map.
	</p>
	<definition xml:id="def-image">
		<statement>
			Let <m>T\colon V\to W</m> be an <m>F</m>-linear map between <m>F</m>-vector spaces <m>V</m> and <m>W</m>. The image of <m>T</m> is defined by <me>\Im(T)=\{T(v):v\in V\}=T(V).</me>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<remark>
		<statement>
			The image of <m>T</m> is an <m>F</m>-vector subspace of <m>W</m>.
		</statement>
	</remark>
</section>